<br>
It works exactly as I expected it to. VI has said time and again that part of the skill of being a magician is pet control, understanding how pet agro works and what it means for your group. A pet is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  meant</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to be contrary.<br>
<br>
I am fine with this with a few exceptions. When a mob is on my pet and an enchanter is trying to mez it, things become difficult. I am not able to pull for my group even if I am the highest level and able to single pull mobs because my pet will agro if I get beaten on. Finally, my pet is a big no-no on many raids because it can agro early from AE etc.<br>
<br>
Sure, I won't be able to go to sleep when I'm playing, I will still be required to watch the battle, anticipate adds, and do the best I can to prevent situations requiring use of pet back off and hold. The sort of things I do now.<br>
<br>
But that is what seperates a great Magician from an average one isn't it? Isn't pet control and knowledge of pets and pet agro / game mechanics what we pride ourselves on? Warriors know about taunt, about timing bashes and slams for spell interrupts, and about the comparitive use of AC and weapons of various types, procs and taunt factors. Clerics manage a vast array of heal types nukes ans stuns, enchanters do their mez/stun/buff thing.<br>
<br>
We control our pets, we master them and make them do our bidding despite how contrary and difficult they can be by knowing how it will behave in every single situation. <p><hr><br>
